Stationarity of Turkish Electricity Consumption Data¶

mit Bar Gkkaya - IE 360 Fall '20 - 29.01.2021

1. Introduction¶

In the following two weeks, we will try to forecast the total hourly electricity consumption of Turkey as part of the project for IE 360 course.
As a practice homework, daily mean of the hourly data will be stationarized and forecasted in this analysis.

2. Analysis¶

All data used are from the EPIAS EXIST Transparency Platform. Main tool for achieving stationarity will be the SARIMAX function of statsmodels package. SARIMAX includes both the standard ARIMA modelling tools and the seasonal ARIMA tools.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import kpss
import statsmodels.tsa.api as tsa

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv("RealTimeConsumption.csv", index_col="Date", parse_dates=True, dayfirst=True)
df.columns = ["Hour", "Consumption"]
df.Consumption = df.Consumption.str.replace(",", "").astype("float")
df = df.resample("D").Consumption.mean().to_frame()
sns.lineplot(data=df, linewidth=0.5).set_title("Daily Mean Electricity Consumption\n 2017-2021")
plt.xticks(rotation=45);
In [3]:
sns.lineplot(data=df.loc["2018-07"], linewidth=0.5).set_title("Daily Mean Electricity Consumption\n July 2018")
plt.xticks(rotation=45);

Data in this analysis is between January 1, 2017 and January 8, 2021.

As seen on the initial plot, data is highly non-stationary. It shows weekly seasonality as it can be seen on the second plot. On a bigger scale, it has a monthly trend, which seems to be higher in summer and lower in other months.

Investigating the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plots below, we can safely assume that differencing the data once daily and once weekly can help immensely.

In [4]:
plot_acf(df, zero=False)
plot_pacf(df, zero=False);

For differencing, instead of doing it manually, differencing parameters of SARIMAX funtion will be used to keep everything tidy.

Looking at the differenced values and the KPSS test values, data seem stationary. However the mean is not 0, which may be caused by the outliers. To solve this, outlier values will be set to previous 14 days' mean.

In [7]:
outliers = pd.eval("ar_model.resid > ar_model.resid.quantile(0.95) | ar_model.resid < ar_model.resid.quantile(0.05)")
df.Consumption[outliers] = df.rolling(14).Consumption.mean()
df = df.iloc[14:]

The mean is closer to 0, the residuals seem more random. KPSS Test is better.

Now that we have somewhat stationary data, new MA and AR terms will be added to the SARIMAX model to improve forecasting.

The significant autocorrelation at lag 7 and partial autocorrelations at lags 7, 14, 21, 28 may be indicating the need for an seasonal moving average term.

3. Forecasting¶

To see how the model performs on real data, daily mean electricity consumption between January 9 and 23 will be forecasted and then compared to the real values.

In [16]:
january9 = pd.read_csv("january9.csv", index_col="Date", parse_dates=True, dayfirst=True)
january9.columns = ["Hour", "Consumption"]
january9.Consumption = january9.Consumption.str.replace(",", "").astype("float")
january9 = january9.resample("D").Consumption.mean().to_frame();
In [17]:
january9["Forecast"] = ar_model.predict("2021-01-09", "2021-01-23")

january9.plot(y=["Forecast", "Consumption"])
plt.tight_layout();

It seems that our model has a "level" gap with the real data. Two random months will be investigated to see whether tihs gap exists in all model or is only the case for our time period.

In [18]:
ar_model.fittedvalues.loc["2018-03"].plot(label="Fitted")
df.Consumption.loc["2018-03"].plot(title="March 2018")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout();
In [19]:
ar_model.fittedvalues.loc["2020-01"].plot(label="Fitted")
df.Consumption.loc["2020-01"].plot(title="January 2018")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout();

It seems that the first two weeks of January is a problem in our model. Since we have a weekly differenced model, low consumption in New Year's Day affects next weeks data. As our forecast highly depends on this, updating the model with at least 9th of January's data will most likely fix this gap in our forecast. However, as it is not the objective in the homework, this will be not be done.

In [20]:
e = january9.Consumption - january9.Forecast

abs_per_err = abs(e) / january9.Consumption * 100
bias = sum(e) / sum(january9.Consumption)
wmape = sum(abs(e)) / sum(january9.Consumption) * 100
print(abs_per_err)
print("\n\nWMAPE: {:3f}".format(wmape))

Daily absolute percentage errors are off and we have weighted absolute mean percentage error of 7.6%, rather high.
We have a daily bias (same as WMAPE, because all errors are of the same sign) as it can be seen on the plot above.
Maybe a better stationarized data will help with the forecast.
